 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uadaaeldarksmith.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adaael Darksmith</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#333333>(7/12/02 12:54:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=204.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Aelo's NWN review</span><hr size=1> Xcerebrus: what you've overlooked is that with a game based on D&amp;D rules, if you don't know the rules, you *CAN* learn them. One of the biggest frustrations I have with games like EQ and DAoC and many others is that they won't tell us enough about the rules to make intelligent decisions about our characters.<br>
<br>
Take EQ. What they originally told us about how stats worked was wrong. I think we finally know, for the most part, what each stat affects, but we don't know how important these effects are. It eventually gets worked out via log parsing, but until then, whenever you have to make an equipment decision or decide how to spend training points, or whatever, you have to guess. There's no way to tell in EQ, for instance, from what Verant tells us, whether you'd be better off with, say, a +25HP item or a +1MR item when fighting a casting mob. You can guess that raising MR will make you get nuked less...but on average will that save you as much as starting with 25 extra HP will save you?<br>
<br>
With a D&amp;D rules game, you could actually make an informed decision in such a situation.<br>
<br>
Some game companies point out that if you were a &quot;real&quot; warrior, you would NOT know things like stats and exact formulas, and so giving the player that detracts from the game (there are even some that want to go so far as not tell you your HP...just that you feel &quot;healthy&quot; or &quot;slightly injured&quot; or whatever).  I disagree with that, because if I were a &quot;real&quot; warrior, I would have years of experience with weapons, and have been through many fights, and would have a deep intuitive understanding that is equivalent to knowing the stats and formulas.<br>
<br>
I recommend that you go out and buy the D&amp;D Players Handbook. Even if you never intend to play D&amp;D, it is worthwhile to read, just to see what a mature, well tuned, balanced gaming system is like.<br>
<br>
